{"id":"mai-kjyq","kind":"ticket","type":"task","title":"Oracle 2: CRDT doc sync with Obsidian","tags":["research","oracle"],"body":"# Oracle 2: CRDT doc sync with Obsidian\n\n## 1. Instructor Framing Assessment\n\nMostly accurate, but one important correction:\n\n- Verified: `SyncDocs` uses `creationBody` as the merge base when file and note diverge (`pkg/notes/docs.go:143-148`, `199-203`).\n- Verified: `lastSyncBody()` is a stub that returns `\"\"` (`pkg/notes/docs.go:510-519`).\n- Verified: the daemon runs a full `SyncDocs` after each debounced write/create event (`cmd/mai/daemon.go:64-76`, `125-149`).\n- Verified: note-side body edits keep updating the stored YDoc state (`pkg/notes/engine.go:651-720`).\n\nThe instructor's framing is slightly biased toward \"Obsidian is the weird part\". My read from primary evidence is:\n\n**The root cause is stale-base merging, not Obsidian specifically.**\nAny editor that repeatedly rewrites the whole file from the current text will trigger the same corruption if every merge is rebased against the original creation body. Obsidian just makes it show up fast because it autosaves often.\n\nAlso: the atomic-save/tombstone issue is real historically, but it is a separate bug that already has a targeted fix (`cmd/mai/daemon.go:67-76`, `117-129`, `154-161`). That is not the current duplication bug.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Initial Hypotheses (from PRIMARY evidence)\n\nBefore web research, based only on code/tests/history, my working hypotheses were:\n\n1. **Stale merge base hypothesis** — repeated full-file saves are being treated as concurrent edits from the original note body, so old inserts are preserved again and again.\n2. **Wrong CRDT blame hypothesis** — the bug may look like \"Yrs/Yjs duplication\", but the real issue may be how Maitake feeds operations into the CRDT.\n3. **History tracking gap hypothesis** — the code already knows it needs a last-sync base (`lastSyncBody()` exists), but that state is not persisted yet.\n4. **Obsidian frequency amplifier hypothesis** — Obsidian's save behavior likely amplifies the bug, but does not create it.\n\nThese held up.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Research Path — every avenue explored\n\n### Source files read completely\n\nMandatory files from the ticket:\n- `pkg/crdt/crdt.go`\n- `pkg/crdt/diff.go`\n- `pkg/notes/docs.go`\n- `cmd/mai/daemon.go`\n- `pkg/crdt/crdt_test.go`\n- `pkg/crdt/diff_test.go`\n- `test/docs_daemon_fsnotify_test.go`\n- `test/docs_daemon_test.go`\n- `test/docs_adversarial_test.go`\n- `pkg/crdt/yrs-wasi/src/lib.rs`\n\nAdditional relevant code:\n- `pkg/notes/engine.go` (`updateYDoc`, `prevNoteBody`, `autoSyncDoc`)\n- `pkg/notes/fold.go`\n- `pkg/notes/types.go`\n- `pkg/notes/AGENTS.md`\n\n### Prior tickets / plans / research reviewed\n\n- `mai-prg8` — earlier report that frontmatter was dropped and CRDT body merge duplicated text.\n- `mai-n5q3` — original CRDT docs-layer architecture epic.\n- `mai-4z3y` — current Delphi epic.\n- `mai-diso`, `mai-yi0r` — recent docs sync fixes, mostly ownership / collision related.\n- Open/closed ticket listings to find related work.\n\n### Git history reviewed\n\n`git log --oneline -30 -- pkg/crdt/ pkg/notes/docs.go cmd/mai/daemon.go`\n\nMost relevant commits:\n- `8ea1ad8` — initial CRDT text engine\n- `1aae181` — fixed identical client IDs; switched expectation toward full-state merge\n- `4ecfad6` — text diff engine\n- `d6c9944` — introduced CRDT 3-way merge in `SyncDocs`\n- `32d370a` — frontmatter preservation\n- `9c6e6bb` — atomic-save delete debounce\n\n### Web / external research\n\n1. Obsidian save behavior\n   - Community plugin `obsidian-autosave-control` README states: **\"By default, Obsidian saves every ~2 seconds while you type.\"**\n   - Obsidian forum / community discussion consistently describes frequent autosave and repeated file writes, and users explicitly complain that it creates sync/versioning conflicts.\n   - I did not find a strong official low-level spec for \"atomic rename vs in-place write\". So I treat atomic save as plausible but not essential to the root cause.\n\n2. Yjs / Yrs behavior\n   - Yjs docs on document updates confirm the core model: peers exchange updates based on **state vectors**, and diffs are meaningful relative to a peer's actual state.\n   - External examples of simple textarea bindings update `Y.Text` by diffing **current text -\u003e new text**, not from an ancient origin.\n   - External reports of duplicated content in Yjs usually come from **overwriting full document state / modeling full text replacements as concurrent inserts**, which matches Maitake's stale-base behavior.\n\n3. Comparable tools\n   - **Foam**: markdown files, Git-based, no CRDT layer in the file sync path.\n   - **Dendron**: sync is explicitly Git commit/pull/push for markdown vaults.\n   - **Logseq**: markdown/org-mode backend in normal mode; their README says the newer DB version introduces a separate RTC sync model. That is a strong signal that real-time CRDT/RTC belongs to a different storage model than plain markdown-file interop.\n\n### Empirical reproduction work\n\nI did two independent reproductions.\n\n#### Repro A — CRDT layer only\n\nUsing the same algorithm as `mergeViaCRDT` (base doc + note diff + file diff + full-state apply):\n\n- `base=\"AB\"`, `note=\"AXB\"`, `file=\"AXYB\"` -\u003e `merged=\"AXYXB\"`\n- `base=\"Hello\"`, `note=\"Hello X\"`, `file=\"Hello XY\"` -\u003e `merged=\"Hello XY X\"`\n- `base=\"one two\"`, `note=\"one two three\"`, `file=\"one two three four\"` -\u003e `merged=\"one two three four three\"`\n\nThis is the key proof. The CRDT is doing exactly what it was asked to do: preserve both peers' inserts. The problem is that the \"peers\" were reconstructed from the wrong base.\n\n#### Repro B — end-to-end `SyncDocs`\n\nCreated a temp repo, created one doc note with body `Hello`, materialized it, then simulated repeated full-file saves:\n\n- step 1 save `Hello X` -\u003e folded note `Hello X`\n- step 2 save `Hello XY` -\u003e folded note `Hello XY\\n X`\n- step 3 save `Hello XYZ` -\u003e folded note `Hello XYZ\\n XY\\n X`\n- step 4 save `Hello WXYZ` -\u003e folded note `Hello WXYZ\\n XY\\n X\\n XYZ`\n\nSo the bug reproduces without Obsidian, screenshots, or UI.\n\n### Existing test coverage reviewed\n\nRelevant current tests pass, but they do **not** cover the stale-base repeated-full-save case.\n\nI ran:\n\n- `nix-shell -p go --run 'cd /Users/alexander/Projects/maitake \u0026\u0026 go test ./pkg/crdt ./test -count=1 -run \"Test(New|Insert|Delete|SaveAndLoad|ConcurrentMerge|Diff|ApplyOps|Docs|Daemon)\"'`\n\nResult: both packages passed.\n\nConclusion: current tests validate CRDT primitives and a lot of docs-sync edge cases, but they miss the actual regression shape.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Dead Ends and why\n\n### Dead end: \"client IDs are still colliding\"\nThat was a real bug historically, fixed in `1aae181`. Current code generates a random client ID in `crdt.Load()` and uses `doc_load_with_client`. That is not the present failure mode.\n\n### Dead end: \"the diff algorithm is bad\"\n`pkg/crdt/diff.go` and its tests look fine for the intended purpose. Diffing itself is not the bug. Diffing against the **wrong base** is the bug.\n\n### Dead end: \"atomic save remove/create is garbling content\"\nAtomic save can cause delete/tombstone problems, but the duplication repro happens with plain overwrites and explicit `SyncDocs` calls. So that path is separate.\n\n### Dead end: \"Yrs/Yjs full-state merge is broken\"\nThe primitive merge behavior is doing what CRDTs do: preserve concurrent inserts. Maitake is manufacturing fake concurrency by replaying large full-document edits from the creation snapshot over and over.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Key Discoveries with evidence\n\n### Discovery 1: Maitake already knows it needs a last-sync base, but doesn't have one yet\nEvidence:\n- `lastSyncBody()` exists, is documented as the right concept, and returns `\"\"` (`pkg/notes/docs.go:510-519`).\n\nThat is a smoking gun. The design gap is visible in the code.\n\n### Discovery 2: `mergeViaCRDT` uses `creationBody` as the effective base forever\nEvidence:\n- `SyncDocs` fetches `creationBody` via `engine.Get(id)` and passes it into `mergeViaCRDT` (`pkg/notes/docs.go:143-148`, `199-203`).\n- `mergeViaCRDT` sets `base := creationBody`, only falling back to `noteContent` if creation body is empty (`pkg/notes/docs.go:553-556`).\n\nThis means the merge base never advances as the file/note evolve.\n\n### Discovery 3: note-side YDoc state *does* advance, so the two peers are no longer branching from the same real frontier\nEvidence:\n- note body edits call `updateYDoc`, which diffs current YDoc content against the new body and persists a fresh `ydoc` event (`pkg/notes/engine.go:651-720`).\n\nSo the note side is current; the file side is reconstructed from a stale ancestor. That asymmetry is the bug.\n\n### Discovery 4: repeated full-file saves become \"concurrent inserts from the origin\"\nMinimal repro evidence:\n- `Hello` -\u003e `Hello X` -\u003e `Hello XY` produces `Hello XY X`\n\nThis exactly matches the reported symptom: old fragments remain and get reintroduced.\n\n### Discovery 5: current daemon behavior amplifies the bug because it syncs the whole docs set on every debounced write\nEvidence:\n- `syncFile()` just calls `notes.SyncDocs(...)` after each debounced file write (`cmd/mai/daemon.go:137-149`, plus `syncFile` below that).\n\nThis is not wrong by itself, but it means frequent autosave editors hit the broken merge path repeatedly.\n\n### Discovery 6: the current architecture epic over-promised what CRDT can do at a plain-file boundary\nEvidence:\n- `mai-n5q3` promises deterministic character-level merge for doc notes and external editors.\n- In reality, external editors hand Maitake **final text snapshots**, not editor-native operations or Yjs updates.\n\nThat means Maitake must reconstruct operations itself, and reconstruction is only correct relative to the actual last synchronized snapshot.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Contradicting Evidence\n\nThese are the places where the obvious story was incomplete or wrong:\n\n1. **Contradiction to \"Obsidian is the cause\"**\n   - I reproduced the bug without Obsidian at all.\n   - Therefore Obsidian is not the root cause; it is the fastest trigger.\n\n2. **Contradiction to \"CRDT means no conflicts / no corruption\"**\n   - The CRDT merge is deterministic here, but deterministically wrong for the product goal.\n   - A CRDT preserves concurrent intent; if you tell it two peers independently inserted similar text, it will keep both.\n\n3. **Contradiction to \"same base state\" assumption in comments**\n   - The comment in `mergeViaCRDT` says the file peer must start from the same base state as the note doc.\n   - The implementation approximates that with the creation body, which stops being true after the first sync.\n\n4. **Contradiction to \"existing tests mean we're safe\"**\n   - Relevant current tests pass.\n   - Yet a four-step repeated-save scenario corrupts the note immediately.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Synthesis — direct answer to the core question\n\n### Short answer\n\n**The correct merge base is the last synchronized snapshot, not the creation body.**\n\nFor Maitake's current product shape, the best design is:\n\n1. Track a per-doc **last synced body** (or equivalent sync snapshot metadata).\n2. Treat file changes as edits from that snapshot.\n3. On divergence, do a standard **3-way merge against last sync**.\n4. Update the sync snapshot after every successful import/export.\n\n### Do we need a CRDT here?\n\n**My recommendation: no, not for the markdown-file sync boundary.**\n\nReason:\n- Obsidian and similar editors do not emit CRDT operations.\n- Maitake receives whole-file snapshots.\n- Once you are reconstructing changes from snapshots, the essential requirement is a correct **last synchronized base**.\n- At that point, a regular 3-way text merge is simpler, easier to test, easier to debug, and matches how other markdown tools actually work.\n\n### Best design (highest payoff)\n\n#### Recommended design: replace CRDT merge in `SyncDocs` with explicit 3-way text merge\n\nPersist one new piece of per-note sync metadata:\n- `last_sync_body` (or body hash + stored body / blob reference)\n- optional: `last_sync_at`, `last_sync_source`\n\nThen `SyncDocs` becomes:\n\n1. Load:\n   - `base = last_sync_body`\n   - `note = state.Body`\n   - `file = current file body`\n\n2. Resolve cases:\n   - `note == file` -\u003e noop\n   - `note == base \u0026\u0026 file != base` -\u003e file-only change, import file\n   - `file == base \u0026\u0026 note != base` -\u003e note-only change, write note\n   - `note != base \u0026\u0026 file != base` -\u003e 3-way merge(note, file, base)\n\n3. If merge is clean:\n   - write merged body to note and file\n   - set `last_sync_body = merged`\n\n4. If merge is not clean:\n   - do **not** silently corrupt\n   - either write conflict markers, or create a conflict note / backup file and report conflict in the CLI result\n\nThis is the most robust design for Obsidian, Foam, Dendron, Logseq-markdown-mode, and normal editors.\n\n#### If the project insists on keeping CRDT\n\nThen the CRDT design must change to:\n\n- persist **`last_sync_ydoc_state`** (or equivalent base snapshot) alongside `last_sync_body`\n- build the file peer from that exact last-sync state, not from `creationBody`\n- merge file edits against the current note state only when both truly diverged since last sync\n- advance the stored sync snapshot after every successful merge\n\nIn other words: if CRDT stays, the system still needs last-sync tracking. Without it, the CRDT path is fundamentally mis-modeled.\n\n### Why I do **not** recommend last-write-wins\n\nBecause the whole point of this feature is to preserve both note-side and editor-side work. Last-write-wins would stop the duplication, but by throwing away one side. That's not an acceptable fix.\n\n### Why other tools matter here\n\n- **Foam** and **Dendron** lean on markdown files + Git, not a CRDT boundary.\n- **Logseq** only introduces RTC in its newer DB mode, separate from markdown-file workflows.\n\nThat is exactly the split Maitake should respect:\n- file-based interoperability -\u003e 3-way text merge with a tracked base\n- true real-time collaboration -\u003e CRDT/RTC, but on a storage model that actually carries operation history\n\n---\n\n## 8. Concrete Testing Strategy\n\n### Unit tests for merge logic\n\n#### Regression tests that MUST exist\n1. **stale-base repeated save regression**\n   - base `Hello`\n   - sync `Hello X`\n   - sync `Hello XY`\n   - sync `Hello XYZ`\n   - expected final body exactly `Hello XYZ`\n   - not `Hello XYZ X`, not `Hello XYZ XY X`\n\n2. **concurrent note + file change from last sync**\n   - base: intro paragraph\n   - note adds section A\n   - file adds section B\n   - merged result contains A once and B once\n\n3. **file-only edit after previous file-only edit**\n   - proves the base advances after every successful import\n\n4. **note-only edit after previous note-only edit**\n   - proves note-\u003efile sync also advances the base\n\n5. **replace + delete cases**\n   - not just append cases\n\n6. **unicode / rune-aware edits**\n   - emojis, accented text, CJK text\n\n### Integration tests simulating Obsidian behavior\n\n1. **repeated full-file rewrites**\n   - write the whole file 5-10 times with incremental content changes\n   - after each daemon/sync pass, `state.Body == fileBody`\n\n2. **autosave cadence**\n   - simulate several writes separated by \u003c1s and \u003e1s gaps\n   - make sure debouncing does not lose the final content\n\n3. **atomic save**\n   - remove + recreate within debounce window\n   - verify no tombstone and no content loss\n   - this already exists in spirit; keep it\n\n4. **restart persistence**\n   - save file, sync, recreate engine/process, save again\n   - verify last-sync base survives restart\n\n5. **large doc regression**\n   - use a 10k-20k char markdown body\n   - repeated rewrites must not cause size explosion\n\n### Adversarial / property-style tests\n\n1. **idempotence**\n   - running `SyncDocs` twice with no changes must not modify note or file\n\n2. **convergence**\n   - after any successful sync, note body and file body must match exactly\n\n3. **no silent growth**\n   - merged body length should not exceed a sane bound relative to input lengths\n   - this catches the 15,778-char explosion style bug\n\n4. **random interleavings**\n   - generate sequences of note edits and whole-file rewrites from a tracked base\n   - final sync must not contain duplicate retained fragments\n\n5. **literal screenshot regression**\n   - if the team has the exact duplicated fragment from the screenshot, add it as a fixture and assert it never repeats more than once\n\n### If CRDT remains\n\nAdd one CRDT-specific test that proves the exact bug and the exact fix:\n- merging from `creationBody` fails / duplicates\n- merging from `last_sync_ydoc_state` (or last synced body) succeeds\n\nThat test should stay forever.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Confidence \u0026 Caveats\n\n### Confidence\n**High confidence** on the root cause.\n\nWhy high:\n- direct code evidence\n- history evidence\n- minimal CRDT repro\n- end-to-end `SyncDocs` repro\n- current tests passing despite the bug explains why it slipped through\n\n### Caveats\n- I do not have a strong official Obsidian engineering doc proving the exact low-level write syscall pattern on every platform.\n- But that uncertainty does not change the architectural answer, because the corruption reproduces with ordinary full-file rewrites.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Divergent Possibilities\n\n### Possibility A — minimal practical fix\nKeep current docs architecture, add `last_sync_body`, switch to 3-way text merge, ship reliability now.\n\n**My vote: best immediate path.**\n\n### Possibility B — keep CRDT but only as internal note state\nUse CRDT for future note-level collaboration, but do not use it directly at the external markdown-file boundary.\n\nThis still ends up looking a lot like Possibility A for `SyncDocs`.\n\n### Possibility C — full CRDT/RTC future\nIf Maitake eventually wants true multi-peer live collaboration, then the right move is a dedicated collaborative document model with explicit peer updates, not trying to infer CRDT intent from a sequence of whole-file autosaves.\n\nThat would be a separate mode / storage model, more like Logseq's DB+RTC direction, not plain markdown vault interop.\n\n---\n\n## Bottom line\n\n**Maitake should stop merging Obsidian file saves against `creationBody`.**\n\nThe correct design is to merge note and file against the **last synchronized snapshot**. For the current markdown-file product, the best fix is a normal 3-way text merge with stored `last_sync_body` metadata. Keeping CRDT in the file-sync path only makes sense if Maitake also stores and advances an exact last-sync CRDT base; otherwise the system will keep manufacturing fake concurrency and duplicating text.","timestamp":"2026-04-03T12:17:11Z","branch":"main"}
